---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "When is the best time to ask for a raise?",
    a: "The ideal time is typically 3-4 months before your annual performance review when budgets are being set, or immediately after a major win or successful project delivery."
  },
  {
    q: "How much of a raise should I ask for?",
    a: "A standard raise request is between 10% and 20%, but your exact number should be grounded in market research using tools like Glassdoor and Levels.fyi."
  },
  {
    q: "What should I do if my boss says there is no budget?",
    a: "If the base salary is denied due to budget constraints, pivot to negotiating alternative compensation such as extra PTO, equity, remote work days, or an accelerated review schedule."
  },
  {
    q: "Should I mention inflation when asking for a raise?",
    a: "No, avoid citing personal financial needs or inflation. Focus entirely on your value, documented achievements, and the current market rate for your role."
  },
  {
    q: "What if my request for a raise is completely denied?",
    a: "Ask for specific, measurable goals you need to hit to get the raise in the future, and schedule a follow-up review for 3 to 6 months down the line. If they refuse, it may be time to look for a new job."
  }
];

const meta = {
  title: "How to Negotiate a Raise: Step-by-Step Guide",
  description: "Learn exactly how to ask for a raise. From timing and research to scripts and handling objections, get the pay you deserve.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-05-10",
};

const articleSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": meta.title,
  "description": meta.description,
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "Get The Bag"
  },
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "Get The Bag"
  },
  "datePublished": meta.published,
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": faqs.map(faq => ({
    "@type": "Question",
    "name": faq.q,
    "acceptedAnswer": {
      "@type": "Answer",
      "text": faq.a
    }
  }))
};

const schema = [articleSchema, faqSchema];
---

<SiteLayout
  site="getthebag"
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  canonical="https://getthebag.photonbuilder.com/how-to-negotiate-a-raise"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />

  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>How to Negotiate a Raise: The Ultimate Step-by-Step Guide</h1>
      <p>Stop settling for 3% annual bumps. Learn the exact timing, research strategies, and scripts to confidently negotiate a significant pay raise.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">

      <h2>1. Timing: When to Ask for a Raise</h2>
      <p>Your leverage depends entirely on when you initiate the conversation. Do not wait for your annual review to bring it up for the first time.</p>
      <div class="tactics-grid">
        <div class="tactic-card">
          <h3>After Major Wins</h3>
          <p>The best time to ask is immediately following a major success. Did you just deliver a critical project, save the company money, or secure a large client? Capitalize on that momentum.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tactic-card">
          <h3>Before Budget Season</h3>
          <p>By the time your annual review rolls around, the budget is already locked. Start the conversation 3-4 months prior to budget season so your manager can advocate for you early.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>2. The Research Phase: Know Your Market Value</h2>
      <p>You cannot effectively negotiate without data. You need to prove that you are being underpaid relative to the market standard for your exact role, location, and experience level.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Use Reliable Salary Data:</strong> Check platforms like <strong>Levels.fyi</strong>, <strong>Glassdoor</strong>, and <strong>Blind</strong> for up-to-date compensation data.</li>
        <li><strong>Factor in Location:</strong> A developer in New York City earns more than one in Ohio. Make sure your comparables are accurate for your region.</li>
        <li><strong>Set Your Target Number:</strong> Come up with a specific target number (e.g., $115,000) rather than a round number ($110,000) to show you've done precise research.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>3. Preparing Your Case: Document & Quantify</h2>
      <p>Do not ask for a raise because of inflation, higher rent, or personal expenses. Ask for a raise based on your documented value to the business.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Create a "Brag Document":</strong> Maintain an ongoing list of your accomplishments, successful projects, and positive feedback from peers or clients.</li>
        <li><strong>Quantify Your Impact:</strong> Use hard numbers. Instead of saying "improved site speed," say "decreased page load time by 40%, leading to a 15% increase in conversions."</li>
        <li><strong>Highlight Expanded Responsibilities:</strong> Show how your current day-to-day work exceeds the original job description you were hired for.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>4. The Conversation: Scripts & Anchoring</h2>
      <p>Schedule a dedicated 1-on-1 meeting. Do not spring this on your boss casually in the hallway or during a busy status update call.</p>

      <div class="script-box">
        <h3>The Opening Script</h3>
        <p class="script-text">"I wanted to schedule this time to discuss my career trajectory and compensation. Over the last year, I've taken on [New Responsibility 1] and successfully delivered [Major Project], which generated [Quantifiable Result]. Based on these expanded responsibilities and recent market data for this level of impact, I'd like to adjust my base salary to $X."</p>
      </div>

      <p>Once you state your number, <strong>stop talking</strong>. Let the silence do the work. The first number you propose sets the "anchor" for the rest of the negotiation.</p>

      <h2>5. Handling Objections</h2>
      <p>Expect pushback. Managers are trained to handle raise requests. Here is how to navigate the most common objections.</p>
      <div class="response-table-container">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Manager's Objection</th>
              <th>Your Response</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>"We just don't have the budget right now."</td>
              <td>"I understand budget constraints. Can we agree to a guaranteed review in 3-6 months with a written plan to increase my salary to $X once the new budget opens?"</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>"You need more time in your current role first."</td>
              <td>"I appreciate that feedback. Can we establish specific, measurable goals today that, once hit, will trigger a promotion and compensation review?"</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>"HR won't approve an increase that large."</td>
              <td>"Given that my responsibilities have grown significantly beyond my original job description, could we look into reclassifying my role or adjusting my title to fit a higher pay band?"</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>6. Negotiating Alternative Compensation</h2>
      <p>If the base salary is genuinely immovable, you can still get the bag through alternative perks. Total compensation is more than just a paycheck.</p>
      <ul class="benefits-list">
        <li><strong>Equity & Stock Options:</strong> Request a larger grant or refresh of company stock.</li>
        <li><strong>Paid Time Off (PTO):</strong> Ask for an extra 5-10 days of vacation time per year.</li>
        <li><strong>Remote Flexibility:</strong> Negotiate for guaranteed work-from-home days or a permanent remote transition.</li>
        <li><strong>Title Change:</strong> A stronger job title costs the company nothing but greatly increases your leverage for your next job hunt.</li>
        <li><strong>Education Stipends:</strong> Ask the company to cover the cost of conferences, courses, or certifications.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>7. What to Do If You're Denied</h2>
      <p>If they refuse your raise, refuse to set goals for a future raise, and refuse alternative compensation, you have your answer. The company does not value your growth.</p>
      <p>Your best response is to remain professional, thank them for their time, and immediately update your resume. The fastest way to secure a 20%+ pay increase is by taking your proven skills to a new employer who will pay market rate.</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-container">
        {faqs.map(faq => (
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>{faq.q}</h3>
            <p>{faq.a}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

    </section>
  </div>

  <style>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.15rem; max-width: 700px; margin: 0 auto; line-height: 1.6; }

    .content-section { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
    .content-section h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 1.2rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; }
    .content-section p, .content-section ul { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-size: 1.05rem; }
    .content-section ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; }
    .content-section li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

    strong { color: var(--text-primary); }

    /* Tactics Grid */
    .tactics-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .tactic-card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; border-top: 4px solid var(--accent-color); }
    .tactic-card h3 { margin: 0 0 1rem 0; color: var(--text-primary); font-size: 1.25rem; }
    .tactic-card p { margin: 0; font-size: 1rem; }

    /* Scripts */
    .script-box { background: rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.05); border: 1px solid rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.2); border-left: 4px solid #22c55e; border-radius: 8px; padding: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .script-box h3 { margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0; color: var(--text-primary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .script-text { font-style: italic; color: var(--text-primary) !important; margin: 0 !important; font-size: 1.1rem !important; }

    /* Benefits List */
    .benefits-list li { padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .benefits-list li:last-child { border-bottom: none; }

    /* Table */
    .response-table-container { overflow-x: auto; margin: 2rem 0; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; text-align: left; background: var(--card-bg); }
    th { background: rgba(0,0,0,0.1); padding: 1rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-primary); border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border-color); }
    td { padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-secondary); vertical-align: top; }
    tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }
    td:first-child { font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-primary); width: 40%; }

    /* FAQ */
    .faq-container { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; }
    .faq-item { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; }
    .faq-item h3 { margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0; font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .faq-item p { margin: 0; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1rem; }

    @media (max-width: 768px) {
      .hero h1 { font-size: 2rem; }
      .tactics-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
      td, th { padding: 0.75rem; }
    }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
